This would be a bit clearer if it was:

```c
  if (buffer_type == GRD_RDP_BUFFER_TYPE_DMA_BUF &&
      vk_device &&
      rdp_buffer_info->drm_format_modifier != DRM_FORMAT_MOD_INVALID)
    {
      if (!import_dma_buf_image (rdp_buffer, rdp_pw_buffer, rdp_buffer_info,
                                 rdp_surface, vk_device, error))
        return NULL;
    }
```
to separate the preconditions and the call that can fail.

The **Eye On Cursor** extension is a great idea. I made an adjustment to make the mouse cursor look like an arrow. I replaced one of the SVGs in `~/.local/share/gnome-shell/extensions/eye-on-cursor@djinnalexio.github.io/media/glyphs/` with https://cursor.in/assets/cursor.svg. Then I set the size to `30`. Finally;

In the `~/.local/share/gnome-shell/extensions/eye-on-cursor@djinnalexio.github.io/lib/trackerManager.js` file, I made the following change to the `updateTrackerPosition()` function. This is just to make the cursor image fit under the real cursor. The numbers may change depending on the screen size.

```
const newPositionX = mouseX + 6 - this.size / 2;
const newPositionY = mouseY + 9 - this.size / 2;
```
